What is a Process?
------------------
A process is any running instance of a command or program(script). 
It could be:
	â€¢ A command or system program (e.g., vi, cat, scrit)
	â€¢ It has a unique Process ID (PID) and runs in kernel 
 Think of a process as "what is actually running on the CPU".


What is a Service?
------------------
A service is a special process that runs in the background, usually started by the systemd.
	â€¢ Services are usually long-running.
	â€¢ They start automatically at boot or are manually controlled using systemctl or service.
	â€¢ They usually do not interact directly with users.
Think of a service as a special type of process that is managed and run in the background by the system.

Difference between process & services

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Feature        | Process                              | Service                              |
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| What is it?    | A running program                    | A background program (daemon)        |
| Started by     | User or system manually              | System at boot or by systemctl       |
| Managed by     | Kernel and user tools like ps, kill  | Init system like systemd             |
| Runs in        | Foreground or background             | Usually in background                |
| Examples       | bash, python, top                    | sshd, nginx, mysql                   |
| View with      | ps aux, top, htop                    | systemctl list-units --type=service  |
| Control with   | kill, nice, renice                   | systemctl start/stop/status          |
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note:
-----
Every services create one or more processes, but not all processes are services.



Service Control:
---------------
- service command is used to manage services on older Linux systems.
- It provides basic functionality like starting, stopping, and restarting services.

Example:
- `sshd` is a service responsible for controlling SSH (remote login) behavior.

Syntax:
  service <service-name> <start | stop | restart>
  
Commands:
- service sshd start     ==> Starts the SSH service
- service sshd stop      ==> Stops the SSH service
- service sshd restart   ==> Restarts the SSH service


systemctl
---------
- `systemctl` is a command-line tool used to control and manage services on modern Linux systems (with systemd).

Common Commands:
----------------
- systemctl status  <service-name>   # Check the status of a service
- systemctl start   <service-name>   # Start a service
- systemctl stop    <service-name>   # Stop a service
- systemctl restart <service-name>   # Restart a service



